{"type":"message","id":"1332d36d","parentId":"5543e1d5","timestamp":"2026-05-01T19:31:27.714Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to check why speech is not supported. Safari does support the Web Speech API, but it requires user interaction to start. Also, the real issue might be that on macOS, the Web Speech API needs to be allowed. Let me check if the page was loaded properly and if there are any console errors.\n\nActually, the issue is likely that Safari needs HTTPS or localhost to use the microphone. Let me check the current setup.\n\nActually, localhost should work for mic access in Safari. The problem might be that the Web Speech API check is failing. Let me debug this.\n\nThe \"Speech not supported\" message only shows if neither `webkitSpeechRecognition` nor `SpeechRecognition` exists. This is unusual for Safari. \n\nWait—I need to reconsider. The original code only sets the status message once during initialization, but if `recognition` isn't actually null, that message wouldn't display at all. Looking back at the code flow, the HTML page shows \"Tap to talk\" initially, so I need to trace through what actually happens when the page loads to understand where \"Speech not supported\" is coming from.\n\nThe real issue is likely that Safari requires explicit user interaction before enabling speech recognition—WebKit blocks it until the user actually clicks something. The code does attach a click listener to the mic button, so when Bobby taps it, the interaction should be permitted. But I'm wondering if the error message is persisting from a previous attempt or if there's something about how Safari handles the Web Speech API on localhost that's causing the recognition object to stay null.\n\nActually, I should consider switching to a MediaRecorder approach with a backend transcription service instead, since the Web Speech API might not be available in this Safari version or context. But first, let me simplify—I'll remove that error message entirely and let the regular button interaction handle everything. If speech recognition isn't available, the button just won't do anything when clicked.\n\nThe user might be encountering a Safari setting blocking speech recognition, or maybe the page needs a refresh after the server restarted. I should add a note about checking Safari permissions, then have Bobby reload the page and try again.\n","thinkingSignature":"e33a0844889b47d9193ebbae44b7f0847591ed57ddfda0b2ef9fe93585b9fbac"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nSafari needs microphone permission. Try this:\n\n1. Go to **Safari → Settings → Websites → Microphone**\n2. Make sure `localhost` is allowed\n3. Refresh the page and try again\n\nIf it still says \"Speech not supported,\" it might be that Safari's Web Speech API is being blocked in the web page context. Let me try a different approach — using the browser's built-in transcription instead.\n\nCan you tell me exactly what Safari shows when you open the page? Does the mic button work at all?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":3418,"output":538,"cacheRead":98112,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":102068,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777663871319,"responseId":"0644327fe2d1df681fc62971dbe5dbb9"}}
